title: Retailers’ Latest Headache: Shutdowns at Their Vietnamese Suppliers
content: Factories in the country, a major apparel and footwear supplier to the U.S., have been forced by the pandemic to close or operate at reduced capacity, complicating the all-important holiday season.

title: One Man’s Endless Hunt for a Dopamine Rush in Virtual Reality
content: From Burning Man to spaceships, the technology has carried him through a 10-year fascination that delights, disappoints and continues to improve.

title: How an 11-Foot-Tall 3-D Printer Is Helping to Create a Community
content: Three-dimensional printing can create nearly any object. A partnership in Mexico is putting that theory to the test, building a village for residents living in poverty.

title: Yellen Warns of ‘Catastrophic’ Consequences From Debt Limit Breach
content: The Treasury secretary, testifying alongside Jerome H. Powell, the Federal Reserve chair, implored Congress to raise or suspend the nation’s borrowing cap before an Oct. 18 deadline.

title: China and Evergrande Ascended Together. Now One Is About to Fall.
content: The property giant’s success mirrored the country’s transformation from an agrarian economy to one that embraced capitalism. Its struggles offer a glimpse of a new financial future.

title: How Covid Misinformation Created a Run on Animal Medicine
content: Veterinarians, ranchers and farmers say they are struggling with the effects of the surging demand for ivermectin, a deworming drug.

title: TikTok Wants More Ad Dollars, and It Has a New Plan to Get Them
content: In a quest for more revenue, the app known for short videos is trying to make it easier to match its stars with brands.

title: Facebook groups promoting ivermectin as a Covid-19 treatment continue to flourish.
content: In some of the groups, members are given advice on how to evade the company’s rules on misinformation.

title: United Airlines is firing employees over noncompliance with its vaccine mandate.
content: About 600 people, or 1 percent of the airline’s work force, will lose their jobs. The airline said it would work with employees who decide to get vaccinated after the company deadline.

title: With sales soaring, Warby Parker prepares for its market debut.
content: The eyewear retailer will go public in a direct listing that could value the company at about $5 billion.

title: What a U.S. Debt Default Would Look Like
content: Market watchers are taking the once-unthinkable possibility seriously.

title: Selling Homes Privately, via ‘Pocket Listings,’ Is on the Upswing
content: Some brokers say houses that are not posted publicly give buyers a chance to get into the market, others say the practice violates fair housing laws.

title: How to Build a Paid Family Leave Plan That Doesn’t Backfire
content: Congress is designing a policy as part of Democrats’ safety net spending plan. Evidence from around the world suggests what works and what doesn’t.

title: How the Huawei Case Raised Fears of ‘Hostage Diplomacy’ by China
content: Critics of the Justice Department deal to free the Huawei executive Meng Wanzhou say it could blunt tools like sanctions and prosecutions.

title: Ozy’s board starts an investigation after a Times report raises questions about the company.
content: The New York Times’s media columnist, Ben Smith, reported that Ozy’s chief operating officer had apparently impersonated a YouTube executive during a conference call with Goldman Sachs bankers.

title: Navient, with six million borrowers, asks to stop servicing federal student loans.
content: Navient is the second major federal student loan servicer to ask to get out of the business. FedLoan said in July that it wanted out.

title: Mastercard will provide a buy-now, pay-later option to lenders.
content: The payment processor moves in on a part of the industry crowded with upstarts.

title: George Malkemus, Who Pushed Manolos to New Heights, Dies at 67
content: He successfully marketed Manolo Blahnik’s extravagantly heeled confections. Then a television character named Carrie Bradshaw brandished a pair in “Sex and the City.”

title: Are you still not working because of the pandemic? We want to hear from you.
content: We’re interested in all kinds of stories: people who can’t find work, people who have chosen to take a step back, people who have walked away for good.

title: What to Know About Evergrande
content: Evergrande, China's largest developer for two decades, amassed $300 billion in debt. A messy collapse could hit property prices and household wealth.

title: Amazon announces Astro, a home robot that it swears is more than Alexa on wheels.
content: Astro has a large screen and cameras attached to a wheeled base that can navigate a home. It was part of the company’s annual devices event, where Amazon unveiled an array of product.

title: Recent Commercial Real Estate Transactions
content: Recent commercial real estate transactions in New York.

title: With his reappointment on the line, Elizabeth Warren calls Jerome Powell ‘a dangerous man.’
content: Other Democrats fretted about diversity at the Federal Reserve as Chair Jerome H. Powell testified ahead of an imminent personnel shake-up.

title: 14 Cuts in 25 Minutes: How Hong Kong Censors Movies
content: The Asian film capital has cracked down on documentaries and independent productions that it fears could glamorize the pro-democracy movement.

title: Britain’s Gas Crisis, Explained
content: A shortage of truck drivers has led to empty fuel pumps around the country, creating long lines at gas stations and panic buying.

title: Stocks tumble in worst day since May, as tech shares slide and bond yields climb.
content: Investors, weighing the prospect of the Federal Reserve preparing to reduce its purchases of government debt, sold off bonds, pushing the 10-year’s yield to its highest level since June.

title: Baseball’s Wall Street-Style Executives Get Titles to Match
content: As M.L.B. front offices get more and more corporate, titles have steadily inflated. Yesterday’s general manager is today’s president of baseball operations … or chief baseball officer.

title: A Star-Studded Production
content: Creative Artists Agency’s purchase of rival ICM Partners is the largest consolidation of the talent agency industry in years.

title: Oil prices near a three-year high as an energy crunch looms.
content: Analysts say soaring natural gas prices are helping push oil futures higher, as Brent crude briefly topped $80 a barrel.

title: SoCal Gas will pay up to $1.8 billion to settle claims from the nation’s biggest gas leak.
content: The natural gas leak, in 2015, forced thousands of people from their homes in an area of Los Angeles.

title: Activision to pay $18 million settlement over workplace misconduct.
content: The complaint by a federal agency followed several other legal actions taken against the game maker, which has been accused of sexual harassment and discrimination.

title: Ford Will Build 4 Factories in a Big Electric Vehicle Push
content: The automaker and a supplier will spend $11.4 billion on three battery factories and a truck plant, creating 11,000 jobs.
